{"title_page": "Melanie Harrison Okoro", "text_new": "{{short description|Marine estuarine and environmental scientist}}\n{{orphan|date=February 2019}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n| name = Melanie Harrison Okoro\n| birth_date = November 2, 1982\n| birth_place = Cocoa Beach, Florida\n| alma_mater = Johnson C. Smith University (Bachelor of Science)\n\nUniversity of Maryland, Baltimore County (Ph.D)\n| nationality = American\n| fields = Environmental Science\n| home_town = Tuskegee, Alabama\n| image =\n| caption = Melanie Harrison Okoro\n}}\n\n'''Melanie Harrison Okoro''' (born 1982) is a marine estuarine and environmental scientist. She is the founder, CEO, and principal of Eco-Alpha Environmental & Engineering Services. Okoro focuses on environmental aquatic biogeochemistry, professional natural resource management, and STEM diversity initiatives. She is the first African-American women early-career scientist to serve on the Council of the [[American Geophysical Union]] (AGU).\n\n== Early life and education ==\nMelanie Harrison Okoro was born on November 2, 1982 in Cocoa Beach, Florida to Eugene Harrison Jr. and Sharon Harrison. Her family moved while Okoro was still a child, and she grew up in Tuskegee, Alabama. Okoro first discovered her interest in environmental science through swimming and fishing with her great-grandmother and twin sister in Lake Martin, Alabama.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite journal|doi=10.1511/2016.119.76|title=How to Recruit and Retain Underrepresented Minorities|journal=American Scientist|volume=104|issue=2|pages=76|year=2016|last1=Okoro|first1=Melanie|last2=Johnson|first2=Ashanti}}</ref> Okoro was a member of her high school's basketball team, and she attended [[Johnson C. Smith University]] in Charlotte, North Carolina on a basketball scholarship.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://198.86.242.37/news/publications/2002_Media_Guide_eBook.pdf| page=41| title=Basketball Media Guide| website=Johnson C. Smith University Golden Bulls| year=2002| access-date=27 February 2019}}</ref> Going into JCSU, Okoro intended to become a medical doctor.<ref name=\"OE\">{{cite web|url=https://www.onlineeducation.com/women-breaking-barriers/interviews/dr-melanie-harrison-okoro| title=Melanie Harrison Okoro, PhD \u2013 Water Quality Specialist, National Oceanographic and Atmospheric Administration in the National Marine Fisheries Service| website=OnlineEducation.com|author=OnlineEducation.com| access-date=27 February 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://alncfeaturedscientist.wordpress.com/2019/03/26/dr-melanie-harrison-okoro/|title=Dr. Melanie Harrison Okoro|last=aldoleopoldnaturecenter|date=2019-03-27|website=Featured Scientists|language=en|access-date=2019-10-17}}</ref> At JCSU, Okoro's advisor was Joseph Fail, an ecologist in the school's biology department, who she credits with guiding her to major in biology.<ref name=\"OE\"/> Okoro graduated from JCSU in 2005 with her B.S in biology, and finished her education when she received her Ph.D in Marine Estuarine and Environmental Science from the [[University of Maryland, Baltimore County]] in 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://blogs.scientificamerican.com/urban-scientist/you-should-know-dr-melanie-harrison-okoro/| author=DNLee| date=9 March 2015| title=You Should Know: Dr. Melanie Harrison Okoro| website=Scientific American|access-date=27 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Career and research ==\nOkoro is currently the founder, CEO, and principal of Eco-Alpha Environmental & Engineering Services, an environmental and engineering consulting, staffing, and training firm located in Sacramento, California. Eco-Alpha helps solve their clients' complex environmental and engineering challenges. Before founding Eco-Alpha, Okoro worked for the [[National Oceanic & Atmospheric Administration]] (NOAA). She started at the NOAA as a graduate scientist (2009-2011), and became a Water Quality Specialist & Aquatic Invasive Species Coordinator, a position she held for 7 years in Sacramento, California.<ref>https://www.linkedin.com/in/melanieharrison2</ref> While in this position, Okoro oversaw water quality, and monitored aquatic invasive species impacts on threatened and endangered species in California, as well as in-land and coastal regions of Washington, Idaho, Oregon, Alaska, the Chesapeake Bay, Michigan, and Maryland. Okoro specializes in marine estuaries. Her areas of research and policy expertise include environmental aquatic biogeochemistry, professional natural resource management, and STEM diversity initiatives.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://marinescience.ucdavis.edu/events?trumbaEmbed=view=event&eventid=133288181|title=Events {{!}} Coastal and Marine Sciences Institute & Bodega Marine Laboratory|website=marinescience.ucdavis.edu|access-date=2019-10-17|date=2018-07-27}}</ref><ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Awards and honors ==\n* 2017 NOAA Fisheries Employee of the Year<ref>{{cite web|url=https://eswnonline.org/dr-melanie-okoro-receives-2017-noaa-fisheries-award/| title=Dr. Melanie Okoro receives 2017 NOAA Fisheries Award| last=Barnes| first=Rebecca| date=3 July 2018| access-date=27 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Selected publications ==\n*{{Cite journal | doi=10.1111/jawr.12193|title = Hydrologic Controls on Nitrogen and Phosphorous [''sic''] Dynamics in Relict Oxbow Wetlands Adjacent to an Urban Restored Stream| journal=Jawra Journal of the American Water Resources Association| volume=50| issue=6| pages=1365\u20131382|year = 2014|last1 = Harrison|first1 = Melanie D.| last2=Miller| first2=Andrew J.| last3=Groffman| first3=Peter M.| last4=Mayer| first4=Paul M.| last5=Kaushal| first5=Sujay S.}}\n* {{cite journal|doi=10.1007/s10533-012-9708-1|title=Nitrate removal in two relict oxbow urban wetlands: A 15N mass-balance approach|journal=Biogeochemistry|volume=111|issue=1\u20133|pages=647\u2013660|year=2012|last1=Harrison|first1=Melanie D.|last2=Groffman|first2=Peter M.|last3=Mayer|first3=Paul M.|last4=Kaushal|first4=Sujay S.|bibcode=2012AGUFM.B43H0532H}}\n* {{Cite journal | doi=10.1016/j.ecoleng.2011.09.001| title=Microbial biomass and activity in geomorphic features in forested and urban restored and degraded streams| journal=Ecological Engineering| volume=38| pages=1\u201310| year=2012| last1=Harrison| first1=Melanie D.| last2=Groffman| first2=Peter M.| last3=Mayer| first3=Paul M.| last4=Kaushal| first4=Sujay S.}}\n* {{Cite journal | doi=10.1016/j.landusepol.2011.08.007| title=Smart growth and the septic tank: Wastewater treatment and growth management in the Baltimore region| journal=Land Use Policy| volume=29| issue=3| pages=483\u2013492| year=2012| last1=Harrison| first1=Melanie| last2=Stanwyck| first2=Elizabeth| last3=Beckingham| first3=Barbara| last4=Starry| first4=Olyssa| last5=Hanlon| first5=Bernadette| last6=Newcomer| first6=Justin}}\n* {{Cite journal | doi=10.2134/jeq2010.0335| pmid=21520770| title=Denitrification in Alluvial Wetlands in an Urban Landscape| journal=Journal of Environmental Quality| volume=40| issue=2| pages=634| year=2011| last1=Harrison| first1=Melanie D.| last2=Groffman| first2=Peter M.| last3=Mayer| first3=Paul M.| last4=Kaushal| first4=Sujay S.| last5=Newcomer| first5=Tamara A.| url=https://dl.sciencesocieties.org/publications/jeq/pdfs/40/2/634| doi-access=free}}\n\n== Public engagement ==\nOkoro is known for her efforts in promoting diversity in STEM fields, and she has held multiple positions in several organizations related to diversity and inclusion. Okoro has served on the council of the [[American Geophysical Union]] (AGU) as an Early Career Scientist<!-- need a new reference, old link was broken. --> and was the Diversity & Inclusion task-force chair. Okoro was a member of the Earth Science Women's Network's Leadership Board<ref>{{cite web|url=https://eswnonline.org/eswn-welcomes-new-leadership-board-members/| title=ESWN Welcomes New Leadership Board Members| date=4 October 2016| last=Schmit| first=Colleen|website=Earth Science Women's Network| access-date=27 February 2019}}</ref> from 2016-2018. The Earth Science Women's Network is a non-profit organization dedicated to building a resilient community that lifts all women and moves the geosciences forward. She is also a member of Minorities Striving and Pursuing Higher Degrees of Success in Earth and Space Science's (MS PHD'S) leadership board, an initiative established to facilitate preparation and advancement of underrepresented minorities (African Americans, Hispanics and Native Americans) within the Earth System Science Community. Okoro also uses social media to educate users on environmental science and issues, specifically regarding invasive species and water pollution.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/drmelanieokoro?lang=en|title=Dr. Melanie Okoro (@DrMelanieOkoro) {{!}} Twitter|website=twitter.com|language=en|access-date=2019-10-17}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Okoro, Melanie Harrison}}\n[[Category:1982 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American women scientists]]\n[[Category:African-American women]]\n[[Category:People from Cocoa Beach, Florida]]\n[[Category:Johnson C. Smith Golden Bulls basketball players]]\n[[Category:Johnson C. Smith University alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Maryland, Baltimore County alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Marine estuarine and environmental scientist}}\n{{orphan|date=February 2019}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n| name = Melanie Harrison Okoro\n| birth_date = November 2, 1982\n| birth_place = Cocoa Beach, Florida\n| alma_mater = Johnson C. Smith University (Bachelor of Science)\n\nUniversity of Maryland, Baltimore County (Ph.D)\n| nationality = American\n| fields = Environmental Science\n| home_town = Tuskegee, Alabama\n| image =\n| caption = Melanie Harrison Okoro\n}}\n\n'''Melanie Harrison Okoro''' (born 1982) is a marine estuarine and environmental scientist. She is the founder, CEO, and principal of Eco-Alpha Environmental & Engineering Services. Okoro focuses on environmental aquatic biogeochemistry, professional natural resource management, and STEM diversity initiatives. She is the first African-American women early-career scientist to serve on the Council of the [[American Geophysical Union]] (AGU).\n\n== Early life and education ==\nMelanie Harrison Okoro was born on November 2, 1982 in Cocoa Beach, Florida to Eugene Harrison Jr. and Sharon Harrison. Her family moved while Okoro was still a child, and she grew up in Tuskegee, Alabama. Okoro first discovered her interest in environmental science through swimming and fishing with her great-grandmother and twin sister in Lake Martin, Alabama.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite journal|doi=10.1511/2016.119.76|title=How to Recruit and Retain Underrepresented Minorities|journal=American Scientist|volume=104|issue=2|pages=76|year=2016|last1=Okoro|first1=Melanie|last2=Johnson|first2=Ashanti}}</ref> Okoro was a member of her high school's basketball team, and she attended [[Johnson C. Smith University]] in Charlotte, North Carolina on a basketball scholarship.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://198.86.242.37/news/publications/2002_Media_Guide_eBook.pdf| page=41| title=Basketball Media Guide| website=Johnson C. Smith University Golden Bulls| year=2002| access-date=27 February 2019}}</ref> Going into JCSU, Okoro intended to become a medical doctor.<ref name=\"OE\">{{cite web|url=https://www.onlineeducation.com/women-breaking-barriers/interviews/dr-melanie-harrison-okoro| title=Melanie Harrison Okoro, PhD \u2013 Water Quality Specialist, National Oceanographic and Atmospheric Administration in the National Marine Fisheries Service| website=OnlineEducation.com|author=OnlineEducation.com| access-date=27 February 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://alncfeaturedscientist.wordpress.com/2019/03/26/dr-melanie-harrison-okoro/|title=Dr. Melanie Harrison Okoro|last=aldoleopoldnaturecenter|date=2019-03-27|website=Featured Scientists|language=en|access-date=2019-10-17}}</ref> At JCSU, Okoro's advisor was Joseph Fail, an ecologist in the school's biology department, who she credits with guiding her to major in biology.<ref name=\"OE\"/> Okoro graduated from JCSU in 2005 with her B.S in biology, and finished her education when she received her Ph.D in Marine Estuarine and Environmental Science from the [[University of Maryland, Baltimore County]] in 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://blogs.scientificamerican.com/urban-scientist/you-should-know-dr-melanie-harrison-okoro/| author=DNLee| date=9 March 2015| title=You Should Know: Dr. Melanie Harrison Okoro| website=Scientific American|access-date=27 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Career and research ==\nOkoro is currently the founder, CEO, and principal of Eco-Alpha Environmental & Engineering Services, an environmental and engineering consulting, staffing, and training firm located in Sacramento, California. Eco-Alpha helps solve their clients' complex environmental and engineering challenges. Before founding Eco-Alpha, Okoro worked for the [[National Oceanic & Atmospheric Administration]] (NOAA). She started at the NOAA as a graduate scientist (2009-2011), and became a Water Quality Specialist & Aquatic Invasive Species Coordinator, a position she held for 7 years in Sacramento, California.<ref>https://www.linkedin.com/in/melanieharrison2</ref> While in this position, Okoro oversaw water quality, and monitored aquatic invasive species impacts on threatened and endangered species in California, as well as in-land and coastal regions of Washington, Idaho, Oregon, Alaska, the Chesapeake Bay, Michigan, and Maryland. Okoro specializes in marine estuaries. Her areas of research and policy expertise include environmental aquatic biogeochemistry, professional natural resource management, and STEM diversity initiatives.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://marinescience.ucdavis.edu/events?trumbaEmbed=view=event&eventid=133288181|title=Events {{!}} Coastal and Marine Sciences Institute & Bodega Marine Laboratory|website=marinescience.ucdavis.edu|access-date=2019-10-17|date=2018-07-27}}</ref><ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Awards and honors ==\n* 2017 NOAA Fisheries Employee of the Year<ref>{{cite web|url=https://eswnonline.org/dr-melanie-okoro-receives-2017-noaa-fisheries-award/| title=Dr. Melanie Okoro receives 2017 NOAA Fisheries Award| last=Barnes| first=Rebecca| date=3 July 2018| access-date=27 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Selected publications ==\n*{{Cite journal | doi=10.1111/jawr.12193|title = Hydrologic Controls on Nitrogen and Phosphorous [''sic''] Dynamics in Relict Oxbow Wetlands Adjacent to an Urban Restored Stream| journal=Jawra Journal of the American Water Resources Association| volume=50| issue=6| pages=1365\u20131382|year = 2014|last1 = Harrison|first1 = Melanie D.| last2=Miller| first2=Andrew J.| last3=Groffman| first3=Peter M.| last4=Mayer| first4=Paul M.| last5=Kaushal| first5=Sujay S.}}\n* {{cite journal|doi=10.1007/s10533-012-9708-1|title=Nitrate removal in two relict oxbow urban wetlands: A 15N mass-balance approach|journal=Biogeochemistry|volume=111|issue=1\u20133|pages=647\u2013660|year=2012|last1=Harrison|first1=Melanie D.|last2=Groffman|first2=Peter M.|last3=Mayer|first3=Paul M.|last4=Kaushal|first4=Sujay S.|bibcode=2012AGUFM.B43H0532H}}\n* {{Cite journal | doi=10.1016/j.ecoleng.2011.09.001| title=Microbial biomass and activity in geomorphic features in forested and urban restored and degraded streams| journal=Ecological Engineering| volume=38| pages=1\u201310| year=2012| last1=Harrison| first1=Melanie D.| last2=Groffman| first2=Peter M.| last3=Mayer| first3=Paul M.| last4=Kaushal| first4=Sujay S.}}\n* {{Cite journal | doi=10.1016/j.landusepol.2011.08.007| title=Smart growth and the septic tank: Wastewater treatment and growth management in the Baltimore region| journal=Land Use Policy| volume=29| issue=3| pages=483\u2013492| year=2012| last1=Harrison| first1=Melanie| last2=Stanwyck| first2=Elizabeth| last3=Beckingham| first3=Barbara| last4=Starry| first4=Olyssa| last5=Hanlon| first5=Bernadette| last6=Newcomer| first6=Justin}}\n* {{Cite journal | doi=10.2134/jeq2010.0335| pmid=21520770| title=Denitrification in Alluvial Wetlands in an Urban Landscape| journal=Journal of Environmental Quality| volume=40| issue=2| pages=634| year=2011| last1=Harrison| first1=Melanie D.| last2=Groffman| first2=Peter M.| last3=Mayer| first3=Paul M.| last4=Kaushal| first4=Sujay S.| last5=Newcomer| first5=Tamara A.| url=https://dl.sciencesocieties.org/publications/jeq/pdfs/40/2/634| doi-access=free}}\n\n== Public engagement ==\nOkoro is known for her efforts in promoting diversity in STEM fields, and she has held multiple positions in several organizations related to diversity and inclusion. Okoro has served on the council of the [[American Geophysical Union]] (AGU) as an Early Career Scientist<!-- need a new reference, old link was broken. --> and was the Diversity & Inclusion task-force chair. Okoro was a member of the Earth Science Women's Network's Leadership Board<ref>{{cite web|url=https://eswnonline.org/eswn-welcomes-new-leadership-board-members/| title=ESWN Welcomes New Leadership Board Members| date=4 October 2016| last=Schmit| first=Colleen|website=Earth Science Women's Network| access-date=27 February 2019}}</ref> from 2016-2018. The Earth Science Women's Network is a non-profit organization dedicated to building a resilient community that lifts all women and moves the geosciences forward. She is also a member of Minorities Striving and Pursuing Higher Degrees of Success in Earth and Space Science's (MS PHD'S) leadership board, an initiative established to facilitate preparation and advancement of underrepresented minorities (African Americans, Hispanics and Native Americans) within the Earth System Science Community. Okoro also uses social media to educate users on environmental science and issues, specifically regarding invasive species and water pollution.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/drmelanieokoro?lang=en|title=Dr. Melanie Okoro (@DrMelanieOkoro) {{!}} Twitter|website=twitter.com|language=en|access-date=2019-10-17}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Okoro, Melanie Harrison}}\n[[Category:1982 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American women scientists]]\n[[Category:African-American women]]\n[[Category:People from Cocoa Beach, Florida]]\n[[Category:Johnson C. Smith Golden Bulls basketball players]]\n[[Category:Johnson C. Smith University alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Maryland, Baltimore County alumni]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Melanie_Harrison_Okoro"}
